%N A392627 Tetrahedron read by slices read by antidiagonals: T(n,i,j) is the number of paths from (0,0,0) to (n,i,j) consisting of moves {(1,0,0), (1,1,0), (1,0,1), (1,1,1)} that remain confined to i+j<=n at each step.
%H A392627 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A392627/b392627.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..12340</a> (slices 0..40, flattened).
%H A392627 Richard K. Guy, <a href="https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/journals/JIS/VOL3/GUY/catwalks.html">Catwalks, sandsteps and Pascal pyramids</a>, J. Integer Sequences, Vol. 3 (2000), Article #00.1.6.
%H A392627 Math Stackexchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/q/552655">Probability that between two Bernoulli sequences, one will get 'ahead' and remain there to sequence end</a>, 2013 (see 2025 answer by sequence author).
%F A392627 O.g.f.: (1 - y*h(x*y,z/y))/(1 - x*(1+y)*(1+z)) = 1/(1 - x*(1+y+z) - x*y*h(x*y,z/y)), where h(x,y) is the o.g.f. of A001263.
%F A392627 O.g.f. is algebraic with 1 + (x*(2+y+z)-1)*f + x*(x*(1+y)*(1+z)-1)*f^2 = 0.
%F A392627 T(n,i,j) = C(n,i)*C(n,j) - C(n,i-1)*C(n,j-1).
%F A392627 T(n,i,j) = C(n,i)*C(n,j) - Sum_{m=1..n, k=1..m} C(m-1,k-1) * C(m,k-1) * C(n-m,i-k) * C(n-m,j-m-1+k)/k (assuming C is analytically continued to 0 outside each row, this formula is 0 outside the triangle instead of being conjoined to a negative version).
%F A392627 T(n,0,k) = T(n,k,0) = C(n,k).
%F A392627 T(n,k,n-k) = C(n,k) * C(n+1,k)/(k+1) = A001263(n+1,k+1) (triagonal surface is Narayana triangle).
%F A392627 Slice sums: Sum_{i,j} T(n,i,j) = C(2*n+1,n) = A001700(n).
%F A392627 Antidiagonal sums: Sum_{e=0..d} T(n,d-e,e) = C(2n+1,k) * 2 * (n-k+1) / (2n-k+2) = A050166(n,d).
%F A392627 Diagonal sums: Sum_{e} T(n,n-d+e,e) = C(n,floor(d/2)) * C(n,ceiling(d/2)) = A247644(n+1,d+1).
%F A392627 Center of mass of n-th slice is (A000531(n+1) = A296769(n))/A001700(n) = n+1 - 4^n/C(2*n+1,n) = (n+1)/2 - sqrt(Pi*n)/4 + O(1/sqrt(n)).
